@NODE "playing" "Atoms-X - Playing"

@{b}Starting Atoms-X@{ub}

Launching Atoms-X for the first time on a classic will give you a screenmode requester. Pick a screenmode and the appropriate graphics will be loaded. Please note, the high-resolution modes (anything 640x480 or above) will not work on OCS/ECS machines. If you select this, you'll get an error message, but re-run Atoms-X and you can pick again.

If a valid screenmode is selected, it will be saved in the @{"Tooltypes" LINK "tooltypes"} of the Atoms-X icon and you won't be asked again. If you do need to change the screenmode later on, you can either delete the NATIVESCREENMODE Tooltype, or hold down shift as Atoms-X starts and you'll be given the screenmode requester again.

On systems with a graphics card, no requester will be shown, and the game window will just open on the Workbench screen.

There are some extra configuration options available via Tooltypes in the Atoms-X icon - see @{"Tooltypes" LINK "tooltypes"} for more information.

@{b}Playing@{ub}

The Atoms-X start window allows you to choose various parameters for your game. Tick the checkbox beside any players you want to participate. Any combination is valid so long as you pick at least two! You can edit their names or leave the defaults, and you can alter the type of player, picking from "Human" and three different computer components ranging from easy to hard.

The speed of the explosion animations can be controlled with the "Low Speed" or "High Speed" options. On high-end Amigas, the "Low Speed" option should be fine, but classics with native graphics might benefit from the "High Speed" option.

On RTG systems the graphics size can be changed using the graphics size cycle gadget. This will normally be set to the largest option your screenmode allows, but you can adjust it as desired.

The "Lose Excess" or "Keep Excess" option changes the gameplay slightly by selecting what happens when a cell is over-full. More on this option below! "Lose Excess" is the default behaviour from the original version of Atoms.

When you're ready to go, click the "Start!" button! Pressing space or enter on your keyboard will also start the game.

Each player take a turn to place an atom in one of the board's cells. Place an atom simply by clicking in the square. You can only place an atom in an empty cell, or a cell which already contains atoms your own colour.

A cell which becomes full will burst and add one atom to the first cell in each direction, regardless of the colour of any atoms in those cells. It takes 4 atoms to make the middle cells burst, but only 3 for the edge cells (since they only have 3 adjoining squares), and only 2 for the corner squares. Since the cells which these burst atoms move into might already be nearly full, a chain reaction can be set off.

Occasionally a cell might end up with more than the maximum number of atoms it can hold. If the "Lose Excess Atoms" option is used when starting the game, any extra atoms are simply lost and the exploded cell is left empty. This is the behaviour of the original Atoms game. If the "Keep Excess Atoms" option is selected, any extra atoms will remain in the exploded square afterwards, which can give a small advantage to the current player. Of course, the same rules apply to the other player also.

Once all the reactions are finished, it's the next player's turn to play - unless, of course, they don't have any atoms left, in which case they're out of the game.

The last player left with atoms remaining on the board is the winner.

You can quit the current game at any time by clicking on the window's close gadget, or by pressing escape on your keyboard.

