@NODE "tooltypes" "Atoms-X - Icon Tooltypes"

@{b}Atoms-X Tooltypes@{ub}

Atoms-X supports some tooltypes for advanced configuration of the game. Normally you shouldn't really need these but just in case, here they are:

@{b}SOUND=(DISABLED|OFF|NATIVE|AHI)@{ub}
If the SOUND tooltype is not set (default) or set to AHI, Atoms-X firstly tries to use AHI for sound, and if that doesn't work, falls back to using native (Paula) sound directly.
Setting it to OFF starts Atoms-X with sound enabled but turned off. Sound can later be turned on in the start window.
Setting it to DISABLED causes Atoms-X not to initialise the sound routines or load sound files, therefore it is not possible to turn it back on without changing the tooltype and restarting Atoms-X. You should only need this option if Atoms-X appears to cause problems with other applications using sound.

@{b}NORTG@{ub}
Enabling this tooltype overrides the automatic selection of graphics type and runs Atoms-X on a native screen, as if the Amiga does not have a graphics card installed. This can be used on classics with graphics cards to force the output onto a native screen. @{b}NOTE:@{ub} This will cause graphics corruption if used on Amigas without a native chipset (i.e., AmigaOne or MorphOS machines). It won't crash, but it will be unplayable.

@{b}NATIVESCREENMODE=<ModeID>@{ub}
This tooltype is used to remember the screenmode selection when Atoms-X is running on the native chipset. If it is not present or set to 0, a screenmode requester will open when Atoms-X is started on a machine with no RTG. Delete this tooltype to force this requester to appear the next time Atoms-X is started.

@{b}NATIVESCREENDIMS="<width>,<height>,<depth>"@{ub}
This tooltype goes hand-in-hand with the NATIVESCREENMODE, and saves the dimensions of the screen chosen. These can be modified as required, and will be adjusted to the nearest valid value if incorrect values are entered or the Tooltype is deleted. Again, this setting can be reset by holding down shift as Atoms-X starts.

@{b}ANIMSPEED=(OFF|SLOW|FAST)@{ub}
This tooltype selects the speed of the animation for the explosions in the game. Normally SLOW is fine and is the default if this tooltype isn't present, but on some slow machines, setting it to FAST or OFF should speed things up a little. This settings can also be changed from the start window.

@{b}GFXSIZE=(0|1|2)@{ub}
This tooltype sets the size of the graphics used on RTG systems. 0 is the smallest, 2 is the biggest. This tells Atoms-X which size to set the cycle gadget to in the start window. If the screen size doesn't allow a chosen size to fit, the next size down will be selected instead.
This option has no effect on native screens as these use fixed size graphics.

@{b}PLAYER1="1,Player 1,0"
PLAYER2="1,Player 2,2"
PLAYER3="0,Player 3,2"
PLAYER4="0,Player 4,2"@{ub}
These tooltypes save the details of each player from the game start window. The format is: 
  1 for the player being picked to play, 0 for the player not being picked
  The name of the player
  0 for a human player, or 1-3 for CPU player with difficulty of easy, medium of hard respectively.
These tooltypes are probably best left alone - you can edit the player names in the game's start window and it will save them here automatically if the SAVESETTINGS tooltype is enabled.

@{b}EXCESS=(KEEP|LOSE)@{ub}
This tooltype enables the "Keep Excess Atoms" option during gameplay. See @{"Playing" LINK "playing"} for more details. This settings can also be changed from the start window.

@{b}SAVESETTINGS@{ub}
When this tooltype is enabled, all the game settings (player settings, excess, sound and graphics options) are saved to the Atoms-X icon tooltypes. If it is disabled or not present, settings will not be saved and will return to their default values the next time Atoms-X is run.

